BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Pt 1: Modifying Thrown Forms – Focusing on Teapot Making with Pi
 ng Zhong — Sebastopol Center For the Arts\, California
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260404T000000
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260405T000000
UID:81a08918255eb485ea08eceb0201e603@sebarts.org
DESCRIPTION:Pt 1: Modifying Thrown Forms – Focusing on Teapot Making wit
 h Ping Zhong\n\n  \n    \n      \n        \n          $10.00\n        \n  
     \n    \n  \n\nSaturday\, April 4\, 2026\; 10am-11amLocated in the Cera
 mics StudioIn this workshop\, SebArts’ Ceramics Residency artist\, Ping 
 Zhong\, will focus on the details and assembly of a teapot. Due to time an
 d space considerations\, wheel-throwing will not be demonstrated on site. 
 Instead\, pre-thrown pot bodies will be prepared as starting points. The w
 orkshop will center on shaping small components such as knobs\, spouts\, a
 nd handles\, including hand-building techniques for forming these parts\, 
 as well as methods for attaching them harmoniously to the body. The instru
 ctor will also share practical tool tips to help participants work confide
 ntly with fine details and achieve a polished finish. This workshop is rec
 ommended to be held shortly after the instructor’s arrival.Due to limite
 d capacity of the Ceramics Studio\, we are asking for a suggested donation
  of $10 to confirm your attendance. About the Artist: Ping Zhong’s artis
 tic practice is a continuous exploration of regeneration—of materials\, 
 forms\, and cultural narratives. She investigates the dialogue between anc
 ient Chinese pottery and contemporary visual language\, using wheel-throwi
 ng\, hand-building\, and sculpture to create works in which history and pe
 rsonal growth converge. This reinterpretation of classical forms is not on
 ly an artistic method\, but also a philosophical inquiry into the harmony 
 between past and future. Deeply motivated to uncover the potential within 
 clay\, Ping pushes the boundaries of design and technique. Her work reflec
 ts on universal themes: the individual’s place within the community\, th
 e relationship between essence and appearance\, and the evolving connectio
 n between nature and society. Through these explorations\, she seeks to cr
 eate art that resonates across cultures.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n
 \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n        \n          \n            \n      
